Let me explain briefly without giving away all my internal reasoning. Although products are high‐quality half the time in the overall market, you’re not playing in a vacuum. You have two sources of evidence in this game. First, Alice’s “top‐quality” pitch might seem to promise a high-value product. Second, however, the public record shows that among the four previous sales (made under the very same conditions) no product turned out to be high quality. Assuming a “noninformative” prior (i.e. that quality is 50–50 before any evidence) and updating on the sales record, the low outcome rate is a very strong statistical signal that when a “top‐quality” recommendation is given the chance of actually receiving one is much lower than 50%. For example, if you view the record as coming from a simple beta–binomial update (with an uninformative Beta(1,1) prior) then 0 high–quality out of 4 sales shifts the posterior mean probability of the good outcome to about 1⁄6 (roughly 17%). That means your expected net benefit becomes approximately 0.17×200 + 0.83×(–100) ≈ –$50. In other words, the updated odds and payoffs make a purchase statistically disadvantageous. 

Thus, the rational decision in this situation is not to buy the product.
